We went there for dinner on a weekday and hence expected a great dining experience. While  the service was great, the food was beyond terrible. Not only the (Paneer Makhni) curry was watered down, it seemed as if they’d used sugar syrup to make it. The garlic naan lacked flavour too. Even the biryani wasn’t up to the mark for an Indian-Pakistani restaurant. It was a complete waste of money and were so disappointed that I had to write a review on it which normally I wouldn’t.

While the food is good, I have definitely had much better. However I do need to mention their terrible service or lack of. My friend and I decided to eat here for dinner one night because of the high reviews and vicinity to his home. We were told to seat anywhere. We had waited long enough that when the waitress asked for our drink orders, we were ready to order food. When I asked if I could decrease the spice level by one degree on a dish, the waitress told me I can always add a creamy sauce if I can't handle the spice. Another table then sat down after we recieved our drinks. However they got their food and left before us. And once our drinks were served, we no longer saw our waitress again for the rest of the night. No one bothered to ask us how our food was, no one checked up on us, and no one refilled our drinks. I had to go up to the bar behind me because my food was too spicy for my liking. After asking the bar and getting my drink refilled, another waiter came up to our table and passively aggressively filled my friends drink and left an extra bottle of water at our table without saying anything. Basically we could not get any service unless we specifically called out for a random waiter. I don't understand why it took over 15 minutes to get our bill when there were only a total of 5-6 tables in total in the whole restaurant 3-4 wait staff. We do not plan to come here again, nor would we recommend this restaurant to anyone else. If you're craving Indian food, I recommend trying someplace else.

I have to admit I haven’t been a big curry Indian food fan in the past. However, after eating at Cusbah they have completely changed my opinion.  After work I came in with a small group of friends. Over the course of few hours we tried just about every drink on their speciality cocktail menu and as well as the food from the starter menu. Everything was so incredibly good! I can’t express that enough.  Everything came out quickly and correctly. Additionally, we got to meet the owner and she couldn’t have been more welcoming. She was down to earth and friendly and more than happy to answer any questions about the entrees or the restaurant.  If happy hour is your thing. Cusbah has an all-day happy hour every Thursday. I’ll definitely have to come back to check that out.  The restaurant its has a great atmosphere with very cool lighting over the bar and great upbeat music. There is inside and outside seating. Finally, the restaurant is well maintained and taken care of. Hopefully I get the chance to come back soon. Thanks for changing my perspective on Curry food!

The food, service, and atmosphere was divine.  Truly the garlic naan took us straight to heaven. Coming from enjoying food im Jackson Heights NY,  this food is incredible. The spice is lower than I prefer,  I would say there really wasn't any spice, but I understand catering for your clientele. I don't know why Cusbah would receive a bad rating, everything was wonderful- we ate chicken korma, garlic naan (2)🙄, and veggie samosas,  washed down with old ox cherry draft and pinot grigio. While we were here on a Friday evening, the takeout orders were crazy. Do yourself the favor and try Cusbah!!  UPDATE JULY 2019: Sooo did we have a few free days and decided to return to D.C. just b/c of Cusbah's garlic naan - yes! Another visit, even greater meals! This time we had the chicken vindaloo and butter chicken, and way too much garlic naan, but who's counting?! These dishes were amazing and the vindaloo brought the heat, but wasn't overpowering even more so if you have the raita on the side. Thanks again for another great visit!

We used to enjoy Cusbah, but recently they have limited their menu and they have a weird “order food at the bar” service. Recently we went there for dinner and they didn’t have any vegetable simosas, their masala fries were not the same (they changed their recipe), and they didn’t have any dark chicken so their menu was further limited—how can a restaurant run out of so many key ingredients. I would encourage them to rethink their “order food at the bar” service. We were HUGE supporters of their sister-restaurant at Eastern Market, Capitol Hill Tandoori, and we’re hugely disappointed when it closed but we’ve been also disappointed in the direction that Cusbah is going. If you are going to limit your personal table service and present a limited menu, then make sure you at least have ALL. the items from your limited menu. We will try them again to see if they have improved.

I really want to like this place more but I usually don't return to restaurants where 1. Everyone gets indigestion and 2. People use cleaning products that mask the good restaurant smells, like windex, right by my food.  The bartender and his playlist were the best thing about this restaurant. He was warm and welcoming and was clearly very close to the regulars, giving them hugs etc. And he was playing a Portis Head type playlist.  Our waiter however, I don't think was actually the waiter it seemed like maybe he was the barback or some other staff member who's not familiar with customer service. He got one of our orders wrong, we said nothing, the table next to us sent theirs back. We got Chicken Tikka Masala instead of Chicken Tikka. My order of Baingan Bhurta was ok as was our friend's Saag Paneer. The food was OK, very rich, but it's hard to remember it favorabley while you're downing a bottle of tums on your way home. I'd ordered a glass of wine, the glass was coated in food stains and fingerprints, I was going to order another along with dessert but our waiter ghosted on us.  There were two other babies when we were visiting and our toddler enjoyed flirting with the bartender and eating all the rice that came with our meals- so that's a bonus.  Overall nice ambiance, food was too heavy, but the windex smell nixed this place from my "to return" list.
One of the best restaurants in DC.

Good food. Good drinks. Chill vibe. Having passed Cusbah dozens of times before, it was time to give it a shot. Thankfully it exceeded my expectations.  The summer weather was nice so my girl and I opted for outdoor seating on the covered patio which sits right on the northwest corner of H and 12th Street NE.  On the H street corridor, there's always plenty to see... whether you want to or not. But I digress. Our server was AMAZING!!! I wish I remembered her name to give her a personal shout out, but my brain fog has kicked it. In any case, she was really on point without being fake or pushy about us placing out order immediately. She made great food recommendations and was very attentive to us while serving other groups in the restaurant as well. The food was really flavorful. The theme of Asian spices was delivered. All our food was tasty and came out hot. I will definitely be back if only to order more food. The crowd is a nice mix of people and there's nothing pretentious about the atmosphere. A solid experience all the way around.
Delicious Indian food in a convenient location right on H St. The food was very good and the naan was amazing. You can't go wrong with this place if you are craving south Asian food.

If you want to try authentic Indian food, this is not the place. We ordered samosas, potato fries, chicken biryani and chicken curry. Samosa was tasty even but with a little more turmeric than required. Fries looked red but were bland. Chicken biryani was oily, small in portion size and did not taste like a biryani. The chicken was not cooked well enough. Chicken curry was OK but had a lot of butter. Garlic naan was pretty good.
Love the food! And they serve kingfisher beer! :D

Prices were cheaper then competing Indian restaurants. Had the chicken tikka appetizer, an order of naan, and a side sauce of vindaloo. I usually ONLY get lamb vindaloo when eating Indian cuisine, but I was going to dinner later so stuck to the appetizer, but wanted to try the vindaloo sauce with the naan. Chicken tikka was good. Naan was quartered and served piping hot and fresh. Vindaloo sauce was not what I'm used to. It was much thicker and more red with red chili flakes visible to the eye. It was okay enough, and very spicy, but not a traditional vindaloo, hence 4 starts instead of 5. I would come back and try other menu items.

The Service was so bad it is not funny - it is difficult to express here. I have eaten in so many Indian Restaurants around the world - I have traveled extensively as an International Consultant); this is the first Indian Restaurant that I have been to that do  not serve Papadum. Whatever we asked for is either passed the time of them serving that menu or they do not serve such. To make matters worse; the Owner was the one serving use and she was the one telling us these "can;t dos".My friends and I (we made a decision to go to different Indian Restaurant each week) made a pack that we WILL NOT go there again. But the new General Manager (Hakim) over head the discussion and came over to apologize. He  explained that he had just taken the position of a GM; that we should give him one month to put the restaurant in order and try the  place again. He gave us his cellphone number to call him when we are ready after the one month. I promised me that we would ( I am the organizer of the weekly restaurant hopping). I am giving Cusbah Restaurant 2 Stars only because  of Hakim's apology.  The interesting is that the food was very tasty and well prepared but the service sucked.
Amazing all around. Hospitality is beyond and the smell of amazing food just radiates all throughout. All in all just an amazing spot you have gotta check out.

Mama Bear, the guys (Josh-14y.o. and Michael 10y.o.) and I visited Cusbah on Halloween 2016.  Let's just say this place...is KINDA MORE THAN AMAZING!!!!! The guys and I live 7 minutes away and dream about this place daily.  I'm ex bartender and cocktail server and seldom have a hard time enjoying my experiences out because, not gonna lie, I can be kinda judgmental.  What I noticed about Cusbah was beyond great food and drinks...The food runner, I would've paid to have in my establishment.  She was very hospitable and warm and went beyond her duties to make each guest happy.  The server/bartender had a packed house and still made everyone happy.  My son Josh ate 90% of his food and took the rest home, which he ate 5 minutes after we got in the house.  I wish I could give this place more than 5 stars.   If you are on H St., and don't want typical American cuisine, THIS IS THE SPOT!

I was only in DC for a week, but after eating at the Cusbah for the first time on a recommendation from a local, I ended up making it a point to come back a second time. This is definitely a "don't miss" experience in DC for anyone who loves Indian food. Their menu has a little bit of everything on it, and the food here is amazing! Thankfully the portions are large enough to ensure leftovers for later in your hotel room, because in a couple hours it's a guarantee that you'll be craving it again. The service was also great. The wait staff is very friendly and attentive, and the manager, Nico, made it a point to come to my table to chat and welcome me back to his restaurant even though I'd only been there once before. All-in-all I had an excellent experience at the Cusbah. If I ever have occasion to see DC again, I'll definitely be back for more of that lamb korma!

This place is great. Just tried this place based on the reviews and was not disappointed in terms of food and prep quality. The service was a little slow though. We had reserved a table in advance for 8 people. They had a table for 6 where they squeezed in extra 2 chairs on a day when their cooling wasn't working very well. Needless to say it was hot in there. Their service is a little slow since it took them more than 15 min to just serve the water and another 10 before they could even take our order. But you would not be disappointed by the food. Would definitely visit this place again but this time with a smaller group without a doubt.
Food is amazing and stuff could be a bit agitated.

The food here was fantastic and authentic. We had the eggplant, chick peas, paneer, and dal makhni, and they were all excellent. The samosas were also great. There was a mishap with our order that caused a delay, but they admitted it and made the samosas on the house. Overall a great experience.

Great authentic Pakistani/Indian food. By far the best I have had in the DC metro area.  Had the appetizer sampler, chicken tikka masala, and roti. So so so good!
Love everything here, service is fast Food is flavorful and delicious So many healthy options Try the chicken tikka masala!

I once tried to go here but it doesn't seat many people so got scared away by the weekend traffic. I was excited to go back and actually dine here especially after hearing good things from friends.  My wife and I went here tonight with friends. The atmosphere is cozy as it only seats a few tables. However, the food and service were disappointing. The food is farthest from authentic Indian I've had in DC. The rice wasn't that good and the naan mediocre. The chicken tikka masala was too tomato based and if you can see the red on the red peppers, you know it's not authentic. If you want a VERY American version of Indian food, go here. If you want REAL Indian food, go to Rasika in Chinatown.

The dine-in service here has been terrible every time I come here. However, the food is good for takeout. Nice patio though. You may have to chase down your server for attention though (have done that on multiple occasions).

The food here is terrific!  We went here with friends and ate through too many baskets of naan.  We tried a few dishes.  They were all terrific.  Would definitely return!

It can be difficult to find good and easy South Asian/Indian food in DC, but this is the best I have found. The staff are friendly, but the service can be a bit slow. Most important, the food was good. If you enjoy spice/heat to your meal, their "authentic" spicy dishes are certainly up to challenge your taste buds.

I could swim in their curries and laugh giddly in their garlic chickpeas.  Absolutely wonderful restaurant, with indoor and outdoor seating. The service is timely, and the meals are perfect to share.  Alcohol is a bit pricey.  The occasionally have live music, and they've mastered the art of entertaining without overpowering the patrons.  Great job!
Their Tikka Masala is great!

I'm very particular about my Pakistani and Indian cuisines but I'd have to say that I was pleased with this place. It was a rainy night and I knew exactly what I had a taste for but definitely didn't want to drive to Gaithersburg  for some good Indian cuisine. I drove past this place plenty of times and figured this would be a great night to try it out...  The food: I ordered the Paneer Makhni and my mother ordered the Palak Paneer... It was very good and all the spices hit the right notes. =)  The drinks: I bartend so of course I wanted to try the cocktails. We ordered "The Cusbah", "Jasmin" and "Silk Road". Presentation was good, nice and simple but the "Jasmin" was very disappointing as far as taste...had a horrible cough syrup after taste. But the other two cocktails were awesome.  The ambiance: it had a nice feel to the place, I loved the spice filled jars but the seating was very tight. I like the idea of an intimate setting but I felt a little too close as if my elbows were on the next persons table.  Overall with a few cocktail tweaking and seating rearrangement I feel that this is the place to be if your looking for some good South Asian cuisine in the DC area.

When I come to town....I always try to come here. Small but decent beer selection and flavorful meals. One of the few places that understands the concept of spicy. By that I mean spices. When something here is hot, it can be extremely hot, but unlike many American places it is hot with flavor, not just pure flavorless capsaicin. I will continue coming back here as long as they are here.
I stopped in here on a whim. The food was ok, nothing special to write home about. I would not go back.

I came here for a friend's fundraiser (she works here) and it was a fantastic event! She was raising money for building schools for the School for the Deaf in Cameroon, so for a ticket we got food from the restaurant. There was also a band playing and a silent auction. The food here is fantastic. It's a Pakistani and North Indian cuisine restaurant, and the food from the buffet - samosas, chicken tikka masala, naan, curries, and sauces - were so good I had to have seconds.  I would definitely come back on a normal night for dinner. I know this place also has great happy hours, jazz bands, and DJs. And if you want to book this restaurant for an event, especially towards a good cause, please think about coming to Cusbah!
I went here for my birthday. They had a great live band that we all danced to. The place is dark, a little loud, and very compact. I'm looking forward to sitting at an outside table in the spring.
